How many multiples of $9^3$ are greater than $9^4$ and less than $9^5$?
inference:
The multiples of $9^3$ are $9^3 \times 1$, $9^3 \times 2$, $9^3 \times 3$, etc.
We want multiples of $9^3$ greater than $9^4$ and less than $9^5$.
$9^4 = 9^3 \times 9$
$9^5 = 9^3 \times 9^2$
So we want $9^3 \times k$ where $9^3 \times 9 < 9^3 \times k < 9^3 \times 9^2$.
$9^3 \times k$ is greater than $9^3 \times 9$ and less than $9^3 \times 81$.
This translates to $9 < k < 81$.
The multiples are $9^3 \times 10$, $9^3 \times 11$, ..., $9^3 \times 80$.
This is an arithmetic sequence with the first term $9^3 \times 10$ and the last term $9^3 \times 80$.
The number of terms in this sequence is $80-10+1 = 71$.
Final Answer: $\boxed{71}$
ground_truth: Since $9^4=9(9^3)$ and $9^5=9^2\cdot9^3=81(9^3)$, we must count the number of integers between 10 and 80, inclusive. That number is $80-10+1=71$, so there are $\boxed{71}$ multiples of $9^3$ greater than $9^4$ and less than $9^5$.
